I dunno, guys. I’m sad.

I’m just really sad.

Add in the fact that my tiny baby is going to have surgery. In the middle of a pandemic. And then have a hole in her stomach that will put her at higher risk of severe outcomes with COVID. Which I don’t even want to think about because the terror of it is overwhelming.
To be quite honest, feels like I’ve changed nothing. Like I’ve done nothing. That it is all my fault that the road lead here.

And in all of this is a slow and steady erosion of the confidence in capability. I feel so useless and hopeless and I constantly think “is this my fault? Is all this going to permanently effect what relationships she has with food? Am I fucking my baby up?”

And yet, here we are. Our care team was okay with her getting all her formula through the tube because we’d hoped that she’d up her solids intake. But she hasn’t, not really. She’s still very aversive. We’re still here, where surgery is the likely path.
That’s not even counting the myriad different things that we’ve tried in speech therapy to get her to eat solids. I couldn’t in list them all, we’ve tried so many techniques.

We’ve done so much over this past year thinking “this is it!” to getting her to eat: gas drops, thickening her formula for her aspiration and reflux, giving her juice to get her tummy going, two types of meds for her reflux, positioning for reflux, changing her formula 5 times.

I feel like this is my fault, like if I had pressed harder *here* or done *that* then we might not have needed surgery for her. We’ve been fighting for a long time for her NOT to have a g-tube so this just feels like everything we’ve been struggling with was for nothing.
So, our speech therapist is gonna discuss it with our gastro ped but she’s thinking that things are probably gonna end up with Pens getting a g-tube. I’m having a very hard time with it.

@MrWalker_Tweets @tardis_blue @jessejanderson Please realize that you may be trying to help but you are unintentionally causing harm to this child by setting expectations that are impossible for them to fulfill because of how their brain works.

@MrWalker_Tweets @tardis_blue @jessejanderson I wasn’t diagnosed with ADHD until last year, at age 34. And then *A LOT* of my life made more sense.

I was harmed by grades on “effort”. I will be dealing with the psychological effects of being treated as if I was neurotypical but not living up to my “potential” forever.

@MrWalker_Tweets @tardis_blue @jessejanderson All of these are indications of an executive function disorder, a difference in their brain that you *cannot* just “effort” your way out of.

How do I know this? Because this was me. I got great grades. But I struggled with “effort” all my life and blamed myself for it.

@MrWalker_Tweets @tardis_blue @jessejanderson Does it mean that they are messy or cluttered in their assigned work areas? Or that they have trouble recalling and following step-by-step instructions or moving from one task to another? Or that they dislike or fail to engage with busy work? @ilikemints I’m glad that you’re happy that its behind you and I’m proud of you for putting your family and your body first by knowing your limitations. Pregnancy is hard! Even if everything goes perfectly!

I asked my dad to come over and watch Pens just because it’s hard to handle a baby who needs you to do everything for them because they aren’t at all independent yet but honestly if she was a toddler I could probably let her run around while I rested on the couch.

Also for the record, I was 29 weeks pregnant with Pens for my first shot, 32 weeks for my second. You’re immunosuppressed while pregnant so that may color some of how bad my original side effects were, but I can only offer my own experiences.

I got my booster yesterday and side effects are much milder this time. I’ve got a moderate headache, some fatigue and nausea, and the injection site is painful enough that it makes it hard to pick up Pens but it isn’t nearly as bad as before when it felt like a burning ice pick.

Data point from someone who got the Pfizer booster: I had a rough time with my second shot, it felt like a bad case of the flu for about 36 hours (vomiting, body aches, headache, fever, injection site pain, etc).

I’m just astonished every time with how much my parents love Penny, but especially my dad. He can be hard to relate to! But he is SO involved, and SO engaged, and so willing to go out of his way FOR ANYTHING that it takes my breath away.

My dad comes over often to give me a hand with Pens for when I need to do chores. Pens isn’t great at naps when she’s not cuddled on someone. So oftentimes he sits with her in his lap, still and silent, not on his phone or reading or anything.

Just patting and gazing lovingly.

Like, hey, let’s do some major surgery on your whole abdomen and give you a tiny person that you are in charge of forever and also yeah the state now alleges that you have endangered your child through “neglectful supervision”.

This is funny because my meds take up the entirety of two gallon ziplock bags and one of those bags contained a 1000 count bottle of Benadryl.

It is here that I will note the fact that is funny in retrospect: I took ALL of my meds from home because a nurse at my steroid injection appointment that was scheduled two days before our c-section said it may be cheaper to use mine from home rather than go through the pharmacy.

(I do, incidentally, do take another medication that is supposed to help me sleep [it doesn’t but it is supposed to help with fibro] and that is also on the list for false positives for methadone but we think it is unlikely that this is the one that triggered it).

Guess what medication in high doses can cause false positives on a drug screen for methadone.

I will give you one guess.
Specifically, she gave me the all clear to take an entire day’s worth of Benadryl before bed because there is robust data that shows no ill effects during pregnancy for the fetus.

And she referred me to the high risk OB since my particular “keep Kammah functional and out of pain” medication cocktail is involved on the best of days and medication interaction in pregnancy is not her specialty BUT she did give me the all clear to use Benadryl to sleep.

So at that very very first OB visit I talked with my doctor about 1) my many, many medications that I take for my fibro/anxiety/depression and if they were safe to take while pregnant and 2) what can I safely take to help with my insomnia and thus help keep my sanity.

I have had chronic insomnia since I was a teenager. I do not sleep. I have taken various medications for a great many years to try and help me sleep. Little has ever worked. I, apparently, have to be tranqued like a wildebeest.

Y’all.
